# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: http4k-server
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In computer science, **functional programming** is a programming paradigm where programs are constructed by applying and composing functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It is a declarative programming paradigm in which function definitions are trees of expressions that map values to other values, rather than a sequence of imperative statements which update the running state of the program.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In functional programming, functions are treated as first-class entities, meaning that they can be bound to names (including local identifiers), passed as arguments, and returned from other functions, just as any other data type can.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This allows programs to be written in a declarative and composable style, where small functions are combined in a modular manner.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming is sometimes treated as synonymous with purely functional programming, a subset of functional programming that treats all functions as deterministic mathematical functions, or pure functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] When a pure function is called with some given arguments, it will always return the same result, and cannot be affected by any mutable state or other side effects.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This is in contrast with impure procedures, common in imperative programming, which can have side effects (such as modifying the program's state or taking input from a user).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Proponents of purely functional programming claim that by restricting side effects, programs can have fewer bugs, be easier to debug and test, and be more suited to formal verification.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming has its roots in academia, evolving from the lambda calculus, a formal system of computation based only on functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming has historically been less popular than imperative programming, but many functional languages are seeing use today in industry and education, including Common Lisp, Scheme, Clojure, Wolfram Language, Racket, Erlang, Elixir, OCaml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lean is a functional programming language commonly used for verifying mathematical theorems.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming is also key to some languages that have found success in specific domains, like JavaScript in the Web, R in statistics, J, K and Q in financial analysis, and XQuery/XSLT for XML.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Domain-specific declarative languages like SQL and Lex/Yacc use some elements of functional programming, such as not allowing mutable values.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In addition, many other programming languages support programming in a functional style or have implemented features from functional programming, such as C++ (since C++11), C#, Kotlin, Perl, PHP, Python, Go, Rust, Raku, Scala, and Java (since Java 8).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The lambda calculus, developed in the 1930s by Alonzo Church, is a formal system of computation built from function application.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In 1937 Alan Turing proved that the lambda calculus and Turing machines are equivalent models of computation, showing that the lambda calculus is Turing complete.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lambda calculus forms the basis of all functional programming languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] An equivalent theoretical formulation, combinatory logic, was developed by Moses Schönfinkel and Haskell Curry in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Church later developed a weaker system, the simply typed lambda calculus, which extended the lambda calculus by assigning a data type to all terms.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This forms the basis for statically typed functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The first high-level functional programming language, Lisp, was developed in the late 1950s for the IBM 700/7000 series of scientific computers by John McCarthy while at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lisp functions were defined using Church's lambda notation, extended with a label construct to allow recursive functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lisp first introduced many paradigmatic features of functional programming, though early Lisps were multi-paradigm languages, and incorporated support for numerous programming styles as new paradigms evolved.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Later dialects, such as Scheme and Clojure, and offshoots such as Dylan and Julia, sought to simplify and rationalise Lisp around a cleanly functional core, while Common Lisp was designed to preserve and update the paradigmatic features of the numerous older dialects it replaced.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Information Processing Language (IPL), 1956, is sometimes cited as the first computer-based functional programming language.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It is an assembly-style language for manipulating lists of symbols.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It does have a notion of *generator*, which amounts to a function that accepts a function as an argument, and, since it is a low-level programming language, code can be data, so IPL can be regarded as having higher-order functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, it relies heavily on the mutating list structure and similar imperative features.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Iverson developed APL in the early 1960s, described in his 1962 book *A Programming Language* (ISBN 9780471430148).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] APL was the primary influence on John Backus's FP.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In the early 1990s, Iverson and Roger Hui created J.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In the mid-1990s, Arthur Whitney, who had previously worked with Iverson, created K, which is used commercially in financial industries along with its descendant Q.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In the mid-1960s, Peter Landin invented SECD machine, the first abstract machine for a functional programming language, described a correspondence between ALGOL 60 and the lambda calculus, and proposed the ISWIM programming language.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] John Backus presented FP in his 1977 Turing Award lecture "Can Programming Be Liberated From the von Neumann Style?
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] A Functional Style and its Algebra of Programs".
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] He defines functional programs as being built up in a hierarchical way by means of "combining forms" that allow an "algebra of programs"; in modern language, this means that functional programs follow the principle of compositionality.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Backus's paper popularized research into functional programming, though it emphasized function-level programming rather than the lambda-calculus style now associated with functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The 1973 language ML was created by Robin Milner at the University of Edinburgh, and David Turner developed the language SASL at the University of St Andrews.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Also in Edinburgh in the 1970s, Burstall and Darlington developed the functional language NPL.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] NPL was based on Kleene Recursion Equations and was first introduced in their work on program transformation.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Burstall, MacQueen and Sannella then incorporated the polymorphic type checking from ML to produce the language Hope.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] ML eventually developed into several dialects, the most common of which are now OCaml and Standard ML.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Steele and Gerald Jay Sussman developed Scheme, as described in the Lambda Papers and the 1985 textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs*.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Scheme was the first dialect of lisp to use lexical scoping and to require tail-call optimization, features that encourage functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In the 1980s, Per Martin-Löf developed intuitionistic type theory (also called *constructive* type theory), which associated functional programs with constructive proofs expressed as dependent types.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This led to new approaches to interactive theorem proving and has influenced the development of subsequent functional programming languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The lazy functional language, Miranda, developed by David Turner, initially appeared in 1985 and had a strong influence on Haskell.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] With Miranda being proprietary, Haskell began with a consensus in 1987 to form an open standard for functional programming research; implementation releases have been ongoing as of 1990.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] More recently it has found use in niches such as parametric CAD in the OpenSCAD language built on the CGAL framework, although its restriction on reassigning values (all values are treated as constants) has led to confusion among users who are unfamiliar with functional programming as a concept.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming continues to be used in commercial settings.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] A number of concepts and paradigms are specific to functional programming, and generally foreign to imperative programming (including object-oriented programming).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, programming languages often cater to several programming paradigms, so programmers using "mostly imperative" languages may have utilized some of these concepts.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are functions that can either take other functions as arguments or return them as results.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In calculus, an example of a higher-order function is the differential operator $d/dx$ , which returns the derivative of a function f .
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are closely related to first-class functions in that higher-order functions and first-class functions both allow functions as arguments and results of other functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Higher-order functions enable partial application or currying, a technique that applies a function to its arguments one at a time, with each application returning a new function that accepts the next argument.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This lets a programmer succinctly express, for example, the successor function as the addition operator partially applied to the natural number one.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Pure functions (or expressions) have no side effects (memory or I/O).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some compilers, such as gcc, add extra keywords for a programmer to explicitly mark external functions as pure, to enable such optimizations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Fortran 95 also lets functions be designated *pure*.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] C++11 added `constexpr` keyword with similar semantics.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Iteration (looping) in functional languages is usually accomplished via recursion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Recursive functions invoke themselves, letting an operation be repeated until it reaches the base case.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In general, recursion requires maintaining a stack, which consumes space in a linear amount to the depth of recursion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This could make recursion prohibitively expensive to use instead of imperative loops.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, a special form of recursion known as tail recursion can be recognized and optimized by a compiler into the same code used to implement iteration in imperative languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Tail recursion optimization can be implemented by transforming the program into continuation passing style during compiling, among other approaches.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The Scheme language standard requires implementations to support proper tail recursion, meaning they must allow an unbounded number of active tail calls.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Proper tail recursion is not simply an optimization; it is a language feature that assures users that they can use recursion to express a loop and doing so would be safe-for-space.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Moreover, contrary to its name, it accounts for all tail calls, not just tail recursion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] While proper tail recursion is usually implemented by turning code into imperative loops, implementations might implement it in other ways.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For example, Chicken intentionally maintains a stack and lets the stack overflow.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, when this happens, its garbage collector will claim space back, allowing an unbounded number of active tail calls even though it does not turn tail recursion into a loop.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Common patterns of recursion can be abstracted away using higher-order functions, with catamorphisms and anamorphisms (or "folds" and "unfolds") being the most obvious examples.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Such recursion schemes play a role analogous to built-in control structures such as loops in imperative languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some special purpose languages such as Rocq allow only well-founded recursion and are strongly normalizing (nonterminating computations can be expressed only with infinite streams of values called codata).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] As a consequence, these languages fail to be Turing complete and expressing certain functions in them is impossible, but they can still express a wide class of interesting computations while avoiding the problems introduced by unrestricted recursion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming limited to well-founded recursion with a few other constraints is called total functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional languages can be categorized by whether they use *strict (eager)* or *non-strict (lazy)* evaluation, concepts that refer to how function arguments are processed when an expression is being evaluated.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The technical difference is in the denotational semantics of expressions containing failing or divergent computations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Under strict evaluation, the evaluation of any term containing a failing subterm fails.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] fails under strict evaluation because of the division by zero in the third element of the list.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Under lazy evaluation, the length function returns the value 4 (i.e., the number of items in the list), since evaluating it does not attempt to evaluate the terms making up the list.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In brief, strict evaluation always fully evaluates function arguments before invoking the function.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation does not evaluate function arguments unless their values are required to evaluate the function call itself.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The usual implementation strategy for lazy evaluation in functional languages is graph reduction.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation is used by default in several pure functional languages, including Miranda, Clean, and Haskell.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Hughes 1984 argues for lazy evaluation as a mechanism for improving program modularity through separation of concerns, by easing independent implementation of producers and consumers of data streams.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 describes some difficulties that lazy evaluation introduces, particularly in analyzing a program's storage requirements, and proposes an operational semantics to aid in such analysis.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Harper 2009 proposes including both strict and lazy evaluation in the same language, using the language's type system to distinguish them.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some research-oriented functional languages such as Rocq, Agda, Cayenne, and Epigram are based on intuitionistic type theory, which lets types depend on terms.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] These type systems do not have decidable type inference and are difficult to understand and program with.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] But dependent types can express arbitrary propositions in higher-order logic.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Through the Curry–Howard isomorphism, then, well-typed programs in these languages become a means of writing formal mathematical proofs from which a compiler can generate certified code.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] While these languages are mainly of interest in academic research (including in formalized mathematics), they have begun to be used in engineering as well.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Compcert is a compiler for a subset of the language C that is written in Rocq and formally verified.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] A limited form of dependent types called generalized algebraic data types (GADT's) can be implemented in a way that provides some of the benefits of dependently typed programming while avoiding most of its inconvenience.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] GADT's are available in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, in OCaml and in Scala, and have been proposed as additions to other languages including Java and C#.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programs do not have assignment statements, that is, the value of a variable in a functional program never changes once defined.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This eliminates any chances of side effects because any variable can be replaced with its actual value at any point of execution.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] So, functional programs are referentially transparent.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Consider C assignment statement `x = x * 10`, this changes the value assigned to the variable `x`.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Let us say that the initial value of `x` was `1`, then two consecutive evaluations of the variable `x` yields `10` and `100` respectively.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Clearly, replacing `x = x * 10` with either `10` or `100` gives a program a different meaning, and so the expression *is not* referentially transparent.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In fact, assignment statements are never referentially transparent.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Now, consider another function such as `int plusOne(int x) { return x + 1; }` *is* transparent, as it does not implicitly change the input x and thus has no such side effects.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programs exclusively use this type of function and are therefore referentially transparent.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way to their imperative counterparts.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For example, the array with constant access and update times is a basic component of most imperative languages, and many imperative data-structures, such as the hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by maps or random access lists, which admit purely functional implementation, but have logarithmic access and update times.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures have persistence, a property of keeping previous versions of the data structure unmodified.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In Clojure, persistent data structures are used as functional alternatives to their imperative counterparts.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Persistent vectors, for example, use trees for partial updating.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Calling the insert method will result in some but not all nodes being created.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming is very different from imperative programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The most significant differences stem from the fact that functional programming avoids side effects, which are used in imperative programming to implement state and I/O.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Pure functional programming completely prevents side-effects and provides referential transparency.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are rarely used in older imperative programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] A traditional imperative program might use a loop to traverse and modify a list.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] A functional program, on the other hand, would probably use a higher-order "map" function that takes a function and a list, generating and returning a new list by applying the function to each list item.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The following two examples (written in Java) achieve the same effect: they multiply all even numbers in an array by 10 and add them all, storing the final sum in the variable `result`.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Sometimes the abstractions offered by functional programming might lead to development of more robust code that avoids certain issues that might arise when building upon large amount of complex, imperative code, such as off-by-one errors (see Greenspun's tenth rule).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] There are tasks (for example, maintaining a bank account balance) that often seem most naturally implemented with state.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Pure functional programming performs these tasks, and I/O tasks such as accepting user input and printing to the screen, in a different way.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The pure functional programming language Haskell implements them using monads, derived from category theory.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Monads offer a way to abstract certain types of computational patterns, including (but not limited to) modeling of computations with mutable state (and other side effects such as I/O) in an imperative manner without losing purity.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] While existing monads may be easy to apply in a program, given appropriate templates and examples, many students find them difficult to understand conceptually, e.g., when asked to define new monads (which is sometimes needed for certain types of libraries).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional languages also simulate states by passing around immutable states.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This can be done by making a function accept the state as one of its parameters, and return a new state together with the result, leaving the old state unchanged.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Impure functional languages usually include a more direct method of managing mutable state.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Clojure, for example, uses managed references that can be updated by applying pure functions to the current state.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This kind of approach enables mutability while still promoting the use of pure functions as the preferred way to express computations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Alternative methods such as Hoare logic and uniqueness have been developed to track side effects in programs.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some modern research languages use effect systems to make the presence of side effects explicit.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming languages are typically less efficient in their use of CPU and memory than imperative languages such as C and Pascal.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This is related to the fact that some mutable data structures like arrays have a very straightforward implementation using present hardware.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Flat arrays may be accessed very efficiently with deeply pipelined CPUs, prefetched efficiently through caches (with no complex pointer chasing), or handled with SIMD instructions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It is also not easy to create their equally efficient general-purpose immutable counterparts.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For purely functional languages, the worst-case slowdown is logarithmic in the number of memory cells used, because mutable memory can be represented by a purely functional data structure with logarithmic access time (such as a balanced tree).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, such slowdowns are not universal.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For programs that perform intensive numerical computations, functional languages such as OCaml and Clean are only slightly slower than C according to The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For programs that handle large matrices and multidimensional databases, array functional languages (such as J and K) were designed with speed optimizations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Immutability of data can in many cases lead to execution efficiency by allowing the compiler to make assumptions that are unsafe in an imperative language, thus increasing opportunities for inline expansion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Even if the involved copying that may seem implicit when dealing with persistent immutable data structures might seem computationally costly, some functional programming languages, like Clojure solve this issue by implementing mechanisms for safe memory sharing between *formally* *immutable* data.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This is how for example `java.util.concurrent` classes are implemented, where some of them are immutable variants of the corresponding classes that are not suitable for concurrent use.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming languages often have a concurrency model that instead of shared state and synchronization, leverages message passing mechanisms (such as the actor model, where each actor is a container for state, behavior, child actors and a message queue).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This approach is common in Erlang/Elixir or Akka.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation may also speed up the program, even asymptotically, whereas it may slow it down at most by a constant factor (however, it may introduce memory leaks if used improperly).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 discusses theoretical issues related to memory leaks from lazy evaluation, and O'Sullivan *et al.* 2008 give some practical advice for analyzing and fixing them.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, the most general implementations of lazy evaluation making extensive use of dereferenced code and data perform poorly on modern processors with deep pipelines and multi-level caches (where a cache miss may cost hundreds of cycles).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some functional programming languages might not optimize abstractions such as higher order functions like "map" or "filter" as efficiently as the underlying imperative operations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] has the mean execution time of 4.76 ms, while the second one, in which `.equals` is a direct invocation of the underlying Java method, has a mean execution time of 2.8 μs – roughly 1700 times faster.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Part of that can be attributed to the type checking and exception handling involved in the implementation of `even?`.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For instance the lo library for Go, which implements various higher-order functions common in functional programming languages using generics.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In a benchmark provided by the library's author, calling `map` is 4% slower than an equivalent `for` loop and has the same allocation profile, which can be attributed to various compiler optimizations, such as inlining.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] One distinguishing feature of Rust are *zero-cost abstractions*.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This means that using them imposes no additional runtime overhead.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] This is achieved thanks to the compiler using loop unrolling, where each iteration of a loop, be it imperative or using iterators, is converted into a standalone Assembly instruction, without the overhead of the loop controlling code.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] If an iterative operation writes to an array, the resulting array's elements will be stored in specific CPU registers, allowing for constant-time access at runtime.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It is possible to use a functional style of programming in languages that are not traditionally considered functional languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For example, both D and Fortran 95 explicitly support pure functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] JavaScript, Lua, Python and Go had first class functions from their inception.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Python had support for "lambda", "map", "reduce", and "filter" in 1994, as well as closures in Python 2.2, though Python 3 relegated "reduce" to the `functools` standard library module.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] First-class functions have been introduced into other mainstream languages such as Perl 5.0 in 1994, PHP 5.3, Visual Basic 9, C# 3.0, C++11, and Kotlin.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In Perl, lambda, map, reduce, filter, and closures are fully supported and frequently used.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The book Higher-Order Perl, released in 2005, was written to provide an expansive guide on using Perl for functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In PHP, anonymous classes, closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In Java, anonymous classes can sometimes be used to simulate closures; however, anonymous classes are not always proper replacements to closures because they have more limited capabilities.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Java 8 supports lambda expressions as a replacement for some anonymous classes.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In C#, anonymous classes are not necessary, because closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style in C#.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Many object-oriented design patterns are expressible in functional programming terms: for example, the strategy pattern simply dictates use of a higher-order function, and the visitor pattern roughly corresponds to a catamorphism, or fold.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Similarly, the idea of immutable data from functional programming is often included in imperative programming languages, for example the tuple in Python, which is an immutable array, and Object.freeze() in JavaScript.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Logic programming can be viewed as a generalisation of functional programming, in which functions are a special case of relations.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] For example, the function, mother(X) = Y, (every X has only one mother Y) can be represented by the relation mother(X, Y).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Whereas functions have a strict input-output pattern of arguments, relations can be queried with any pattern of inputs and outputs.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Compared with relational syntax, functional syntax is a more compact notation for nested functions.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, the difference between the two representations is simply syntactic.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Ciao transforms the function-like notation into relational form and executes the resulting logic program using the standard Prolog execution strategy.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Emacs, a highly extensible text editor family uses its own Lisp dialect for writing plugins.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] The original author of the most popular Emacs implementation, GNU Emacs and Emacs Lisp, Richard Stallman considers Lisp one of his favorite programming languages.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Spreadsheets can be considered a form of pure, zeroth-order, strict-evaluation functional programming system.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] However, spreadsheets generally lack higher-order functions as well as code reuse, and in some implementations, also lack recursion.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Several extensions have been developed for spreadsheet programs to enable higher-order and reusable functions, but so far remain primarily academic in nature.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Due to their composability, functional programming paradigms can be suitable for microservices-based architectures.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming is an active area of research in the field of programming language theory.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] There are several peer-reviewed publication venues focusing on functional programming, including the International Conference on Functional Programming, the Journal of Functional Programming, and the Symposium on Trends in Functional Programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming has been employed in a wide range of industrial applications.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Scheme, a dialect of Lisp, was used as the basis for several applications on early Apple Macintosh computers and has been applied to problems such as training-simulation software and telescope control.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] OCaml, which was introduced in the mid-1990s, has seen commercial use in areas such as financial analysis, driver verification, industrial robot programming and static analysis of embedded software.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Haskell, though initially intended as a research language, has also been applied in areas such as aerospace systems, hardware design and web programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Other functional programming languages that have seen use in industry include Scala, F#, Wolfram Language, Lisp, Standard ML and Clojure.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Scala has been widely used in Data science, while ClojureScript, Elm or PureScript are some of the functional frontend programming languages used in production.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional "platforms" have been popular in finance for risk analytics (particularly with large investment banks).
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Risk factors are coded as functions that form interdependent graphs (categories) to measure correlations in market shifts, similar in manner to Gröbner basis optimizations but also for regulatory frameworks such as Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Given the use of OCaml and Caml variations in finance, these systems are sometimes considered related to a categorical abstract machine.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Functional programming is heavily influenced by category theory.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Many universities teach functional programming.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Some treat it as an introductory programming concept while others first teach imperative programming methods.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] Outside of computer science, functional programming is used to teach problem-solving, algebraic and geometric concepts.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] It has also been used to teach classical mechanics, as in the book *Structure and Interpretation of Classical Mechanics*.
[src:http4k-server/functional-programming] In particular, Scheme has been a relatively popular choice for teaching programming for years.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:http4k-server/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] One of Kotlin's stated goals is to compile as quickly as Java.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] In February 2012, JetBrains open-sourced the project under the Apache 2 license.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains expected Kotlin to drive sales of IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.0 was released on 15 February 2016, which is considered the first officially stable release, and JetBrains has committed to long-term backwards compatibility starting with this version.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] At Google I/O 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced that Kotlin is now its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Development lead Andrey Breslav has said that Kotlin is designed to be an industrial-strength object-oriented language, a "better language" than Java, and still fully interoperable with Java code, allowing companies to make a gradual migration from Java to Kotlin.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] For example, `@file:JvmName("JavaClassName")`.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin provides the following keywords to restrict visibility for top-level declarations (such as classes) and for class members: `public`, `internal`, `protected`, and `private`.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin distinguishes between nullable and non-nullable data types.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] All nullable objects must be declared with a "?" postfix after the type name.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin supports higher-order functions and anonymous functions, or **lambdas**.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] If a lambda takes parameters, they are declared within the braces and followed by the -> operator.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin Multiplatform enables a single codebase to target multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, the web, Android, and iOS.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Compose Multiplatform is a multiplatform UI framework based on Jetpack Compose.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] It is Jetpack Compose for Android ported to Windows, macOS, Linux, web, and iOS.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] For example, the Text composable function displays a text label on the screen.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] In 2018, Kotlin was the fastest-growing language on GitHub, with 2.6 times as many developers as in 2017.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] It is the fourth-most-loved programming language according to the 2020 Stack Overflow Developer Survey.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin was also awarded the O'Reilly Open Source Software Conference Breakout Award for 2019.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] A large number of companies in various industries use Kotlin, including Google, Amazon Web Services, Netflix and McDonald's.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] When Kotlin was announced as an official Android development language at Google I/O in May 2017, it became the third language fully supported for Android, after Java and C++.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] As of 2020, Kotlin was the most widely used language on Android, with Google estimating that 70% of the top 1,000 apps on the Play Store were written in Kotlin.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Google itself had 60 apps written in Kotlin, including Maps and Drive.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Many Android apps, such as Google Home, were in the process of migrating to Kotlin and therefore use both Kotlin and Java.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin on Android is seen as beneficial for its null-safety and features that make code shorter and more readable.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Ktor is a JetBrains Kotlin-first framework for building server and client applications.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] The Spring Framework officially added Kotlin support with version 5, on 4 January 2017.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] To further support Kotlin, Spring has translated all its documentation into Kotlin and added built-in support for many Kotlin-specific features, such as coroutines.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] In 2020, JetBrains found in a survey of developers who use Kotlin that 56% used it for mobile apps, while 47% used it for a web backend.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Just over a third of all Kotlin developers said they were migrating from another language.
[src:http4k-server/kotlin-programming-language] Most Kotlin users targeted Android (or the JVM), with only 6% using Kotlin Native.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] 2. the function has no side effects (no mutation of non-local variables, mutable reference arguments or input/output streams).
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] I/O is inherently impure: input operations undermine referential transparency, and output operations create side effects.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] The second point ensures that the only sequence usable as an argument must change with each I/O action; the first allows different calls to an I/O-performing function to return different results on account of the sequence arguments having changed.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] The I/O monad is a programming idiom typically used to perform I/O in pure functional languages.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] The outputs of a pure function can be cached in a look-up table.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] Any result that is returned from a given function is cached, and the next time the function is called with the same input parameters, the cached result is returned instead of computing the function again.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] Memoization can be performed by wrapping the function in another function (wrapper function).
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] By means of memoization, the computational effort involved in the computations of the function itself can be reduced, at the cost of the overhead for managing the cache and an increase of memory requirements.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] Functions that have just the above property 2 – that is, have no side effects – allow for compiler optimization techniques such as common subexpression elimination and loop optimization similar to arithmetic operators.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] A C++ example is the `length` method, returning the size of a string, which depends on the memory contents where the string points to, therefore lacking the above property 1.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] can be optimized such that the value of `s.length()` is computed only once, before the loop.
[src:http4k-server/pure-function] Since pure functions have identical return values for identical arguments, they are well suited to unit testing.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] First described in this Twitter paper “Your Server as a Function”, this abstraction allows us lots of flexibility in a language like Kotlin, since the conceptual barrier to service construction is reduced to effectively nil.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Filters add extra processing to either the Request or Response.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Filters are designed to simply compose together (using `then()`) , creating reusable stacks of behaviour which can then be applied to any `HttpHandler`.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Check out the `org.http4k.filter` package for the exact list.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Create a Router using routes() to bind a static or dynamic path to either an HttpHandler, or to another sub-Router.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Note that the `http4k-api-openapi` module contains a more typesafe implementation of routing functionality, with runtime-generated live documentation in OpenApi format.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Getting values from HTTP messages is one thing, but we want to ensure that those values are both present and valid.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] To utilise a lens, first you have to declare it with the form `<Location>.<configuration and mapping operations>.<terminator>`.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] For serving static assets, just bind a path to a Static block as below, using either a Classpath or Directory (Hot reloading) based ResourceLoader instance (find these on the `ResourceLoader` companion object).
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Typically, Directory is used during development and the Classpath strategy is used to serve assets in production from an UberJar.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] This is usually based on a “devmode” flag when constructing your app".
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Websockets have been modeled using the same methodology as standard HTTP endpoints - ie. with both simplicity and testability as a first class concern, as well as benefiting from Lens-based typesafety.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] `WsConsumer` - represented as a typealias: `WsConsumer = (WebSocket) -> Unit`.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] This function is called on connection of a websocket and allow the API user to react to events coming from the connected websocket.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] `WsMessage` - a message which is sent or received on a websocket.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] This message can take advantage of the typesafety accorded to other entities in http4k by using the Lens API.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] Just like the http4k HTTP message model, WsMessages are immutable data classes.
[src:http4k-server/reference-core] The HttpMessages used by http4k toString in the HTTP wire format, which makes it simple to capture and replay HTTP message streams later.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:http4k-server/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
